// Case Study D — fib-like comprehension at small width.
//
// Hypothesis test (long-term plan §3 Case D): is the popcount
// stall genuinely about the genFix shape, or specific to popcount's
// particular body?
//
// `runningSumComprehension` mirrors popcount's `[seed] # [body |
// elt <- ext | prev <- self]` shape exactly, but with a different
// body (`s + x` instead of `if elt then prev+1 else prev`). Lower
// via the same Phase 5 BoundedVecFold path → genFix.
//
// `runningSumNaive` is the same function written as an explicit
// indexed sum — pure bv_decide-friendly.
//
// The `prove_print (offline_lean ...)` emits the equivalence
// goal `runningSumComprehension xs == runningSumNaive xs` as a
// Lean .lean file. The discharge lives in
// proofs/cryptol_running_sum_eq/proof.lean.
//
// Predicted outcome (per the plan):
//   - If the proof closes with bv_decide + bridges (like Case C),
//     popcount's body is the special case.
//   - If it stalls on genFix the same way popcount did, the issue
//     is shape-level — validates §4.1 Lean-side genFix bridge work.

import "RunningSum.cry";

prove_print (offline_lean "test_cryptol_running_sum_verify.eq")
  {{ \(xs : [8][32]) ->
       runningSumComprehension xs == runningSumNaive xs }};
